g.**\n\n**What the architecture gets right:**\n\n- **The strict-`<` payday gate is correct.** A bill due on payday is funded by that paycheck. Including it in the prior cycle's hold would double-count.\n- **Separating cycle vs. month frames is the single most important design choice in this dashboard.** Most personal finance tools collapse them and produce nonsense at month-end. This one doesn't.\n- **Walling Forward Reserve out of Safe to Spend** is the right call. It's the difference between "I have $729 to spend" and "I have $729 to spend AND I need to not touch the $1,561 sitting next to it" — the dashboard surfaces both numbers without letting you confuse them.\n- **GREEN/YELLOW/RED tied to a configurable threshold** (currently $400) is the right shape — not a fixed rule, calibrated to your largest known irregular obligation.\n\n**What's structurally weak:**\n\n1. **Monthly Savings Estimate = $0.00 right now, and that's not a bug — it's the dashboard telling the truth.** With base net $3,220, full-month bills $1,833.95, prorated variable, forward reserve $1,561, and zero commission, your base-pay-only month does not produce savings. The architecture is correctly surfacing that your fixed cost structure has eaten the entire planning floor. The dashboard is sound; the underlying reality is tight. Specifically: $1,833.95 in fixed bills against $3,220 base net = 57% of take-home is locked before you eat. The Camry payment ($337) plus insurance ($141.95) = $478.95/mo of vehicle cost, ~15% of net.\n\n2. **The Forward Reserve formula uses a flat 7-day variable proration ($138)** added to whatever bills land days 1–7. That's a reasonable simplification, but it assumes you spend at exactly the cap rate. If your actual variable runs higher in the first week of a month (which it often does — rent week tends to be grocery-stock week), the reserve is mildly understated. Not a fatal flaw, but worth knowing.\n\n**Two things I'd flag as a third party that the dashboard does NO