ecome "savings" — it either reduces QuickSilver accrual (helps May checking) or sits in checking (helps Safe to Spend next cycle). It does NOT magically appear in HYSA or brokerage unless Marshall moves it.\n- Priority routing → with HYSA target MET and Roth at $0, the advisor should know where freed-up cash *should* go per the playbook stack.\n\nA weak advisor says "great, you'll save money!" A sound one says "roughly $60–$100 over 14 days based on your log. That money lands as reduced QuickSilver balance, not as savings — unless you actively sweep it. With HYSA met and Roth unfunded, the right destination is Roth IRA, not letting it sit in checking and get re-absorbed."\n\n---\n\n**3. "I'm thinking about adding a $15/month subscription. What's the real cost?"**\n\n*What this tests:*\n- Bills sheet impact → adds to monthly fixed obligations ($1,833.95 → $1,848.95).\n- Forward Reserve impact → depends on due day; if it lands days 1–7, it adds to the wall.\n- Monthly Savings cascade → with current Monthly Savings at $0, ANY new fixed obligation pushes it negative unless something else gives.\n- Annualization → $15/mo = $180/yr, but the playbook frame forces the advisor to also surface the opportunity cost (Roth contribution forgone, or HYSA buffer reduction).\n- Threshold awareness → does this trip YELLOW status more often? Does it push fixed-cost ratio past a meaningful threshold (currently 57% of net)?\n\nA weak advisor says "$15/month, that's $180/year, not a big deal." A sound one says "Monthly Savings is already $0. Adding $15/mo fixed makes it −$15 structurally. Annualized that's $180 of guaranteed negative drift, or a 17% reduction in your Roth contribution capacity if you were planning to fund it from freed cash flow. Fixed-cost ratio moves from 57% to 57.4% of net. Verdict depends on whether the subscription replaces existing variable spend or stacks on top — if it stacks, decline."\n\n---\n\n**Why these three:**\n\n- **Question 1** tests cycle-frame liquidi